---
import DropLayout from '../../components/drops/DropLayout.astro';
import DiagramCanvas from '../../components/drops/canvas/DiagramCanvas';
import { owningTheStack } from '../../data/drops/owning-the-stack';
import { drops } from '../../data/drops';

const drop = drops.find((d) => d.slug === 'owning-the-stack')!;
---

<DropLayout
  label="System map"
  title={drop.title}
  dek={drop.dek}
  episodeSlug={drop.episodeSlug}
  episodeTitle={drop.episodeTitle}
>
  <DiagramCanvas
    client:load
    diagram={owningTheStack}
    label="Architecture map comparing the v0.2 engine-plus-adapters platform with the v0.3 owned, content-as-data stack. Drag to pan; scroll or pinch to zoom; expand or go fullscreen for more room."
  />

  <section class="drop-prose" aria-label="What you're looking at">
    <div class="drop-prose__col">
      <h2>v0.2 — behind a build</h2>
      <p>
        The old platform drove everything through a Hono orchestrator on a Mac mini, behind a Tauri
        desk app. Content reached each site through an adapter layer — a ContentSource (Contentful or
        our own infra) and a CloudPlatform (Netlify or Cloudflare) — and every change ran through a
        build and a deploy, glued together with a tunnel and webhook chains. Two clouds, an external
        CMS, four adapters.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="drop-prose__col">
      <h2>v0.3 — content as data</h2>
      <p>
        The new platform owns one stack. A hub (Astro SSR on Netlify) is the control plane, content
        API, and fast AI, and it owns a single tenant-isolated Postgres. Customer sites SSR their
        content from the hub per request; the engine — a developer agent on the Mac mini — only opens
        capability PRs. Preview and publish become data operations: a DB write and a cache-tag purge,
        with no build per edit.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <p class="drop-coda">
    The generality was the over-engineering. The whole v0.2 apparatus — an external CMS, four
    adapters, a second cloud, a tunnel, and webhook chains — existed only because content lived behind
    a <strong>build</strong>. Pull content into one owned Postgres behind Astro SSR and preview and
    publish become <strong>data operations</strong>. Most of the moving parts simply fall away.
  </p>
</DropLayout>
